DIGITAL PRESERVATION POLICY\
\
Version: 2.2 (Governance & Metrics Integrated)\
Effective Date: [Insert Date]\
Owner: [Insert Department/Role]\
\
1. PURPOSE AND ALIGNMENT\
The purpose of this policy is to establish a formal framework for the long-term preservation of [Organization Name]\'92s digital assets. This policy is a core component of our Digital Continuity Planning and is designed to align with the following international standards:\
\
\'95 ISO 14721 (OAIS Reference Model): To define the functional entities and information packages (SIP, AIP, DIP) required for a functional archive.\
\'95 ISO 15489 (Records Management): To ensure that digital assets are managed as authentic, reliable, and usable records.\
\'95 ISO/IEC 27001 (Information Security): To uphold the principles of the CIA triad\'97Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability.\
\'95 PREMIS: To implement standardized metadata for tracking preservation events and provenance.\
\
2. SCOPE\
This policy applies to all digital information assets, records, and data managed by [Organization Name], including but not limited to:\
\'95 Official Records: As defined by ISO 15489, requiring evidence of business transactions.\
\'95 Digital Archives: Long-term assets requiring protection from technological decay.\
\'95 Data Environments: Including cloud storage, on-premise servers, and removable media.\
\
3. POLICY STATEMENT\
[Organization Name] is committed to the proactive management of digital assets to prevent data loss and ensure long-term usability. We commit to:\
\'95 Maintaining Integrity and Authenticity: Utilizing technical controls to protect against unauthorized alteration and data degradation (bit rot).\
\'95 Ensuring Availability: Guaranteeing that authorized users can access information throughout its required lifecycle.\
\'95 Mitigating Obsolescence: Implementing proactive "Preservation Planning" to counter the risks of software, hardware, and media aging.\
\'95 Continuous Auditability: Maintaining a system of record that supports the principles of a Trustworthy Digital Repository (TDR).\
\
4. KEY PRESERVATION PILLARS\
\
4.1. Data Integrity and Provenance (The OAIS/PREMIS Approach)\
To combat data degradation and ensure the authenticity of digital objects, the organization shall:\
\'95 Fixity Monitoring: Implement automated checksum/hash generation upon Ingest (creation of the SIP) and periodically thereafter to detect corruption.\
\'95 Metadata Standards: Utilize PREMIS-aligned metadata to capture "Preservation Events." Every significant action (e.g., migration, format conversion, or integrity check) must be recorded to maintain a verifiable chain of custody.\
\'95 Redundancy: Implement geographically distributed storage to ensure high availability in accordance with ISO 27001 disaster recovery standards.\
\
4.2. Management of Technological Obsolescence\
Consistent with the OAIS Preservation Planning function, the organization shall:\
\'95 Format Monitoring: Continuously monitor the "technological landscape" to identify formats at risk of becoming unreadable.\
\'95 Migration Strategy: Execute planned Format Migrations (e.g., converting proprietary formats to open, sustainable standards like PDF/A or CSV) to prevent software obsolescence.\
\'95 Hardware & Media Lifecycle: Actively manage the transition away from aging removable media and obsolete hardware, ensuring that the underlying storage technology supports the current digital continuity plan.\
\
4.3. Digital Continuity and Risk Management\
Digital preservation shall be integrated into the broader Digital Continuity Plan, addressing:\
\'95 Business Continuity (BCP): Ensuring that preservation workflows are resilient to large-scale organizational disruptions.\
\'95 Information Security (ISO 27001): Integrating preservation controls (access control, encryption, and audit logs) into the organization\'92s primary security framework.\
\
5. ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES\
\
5.1. Strategic Oversight (Accountable)\
\'95 Executive Leadership (e.g., CIO/COO): Holds ultimate accountability for the organization's digital continuity. Responsible for approving the policy, ensuring adequate resource allocation, and accepting the residual risks of digital loss.\
\
5.2. Governance & Management (Responsible for Oversight)\
\'95 Digital Preservation Steering Committee: A cross-functional group (IT, Legal, Records Management) responsible for reviewing preservation risks and ensuring alignment with ISO standards.\
\'95 Data Governance Officer: Responsible for the integration of preservation requirements into the broader enterprise data strategy and ensuring compliance with legal/regulatory mandates (ISO 15489).\
\
5.3. Operational Implementation (Responsible for Execution)\
\'95 Digital Archivists / Data Stewards: Responsible for the "preservation lifecycle." This includes managing metadata (PREMIS), conducting format assessments, and executing migration workflows.\
\'95 IT Operations / Systems Administrators: Responsible for the technical "custodianship." This includes maintaining hardware, performing fixity/checksum checks, and managing storage redundancy.\
\'95 Information Security Team: Responsible for ensuring that preservation workflows (e.g., migrations or remote access) do not violate the organization\'92s security posture (ISO 27001).\
\
5.4. Data Creation & Usage (Responsible for Compliance)\
\'95 Content Creators / Business Unit Leads: Responsible for the "Ingest" phase. They must ensure data is captured in approved formats and that all necessary metadata is provided at the point of creation.\
\
6. IMPLEMENTATION AND MAINTENANCE\
\'95 Development: All preservation workflows (Ingest, Storage, Monitoring, Migration) shall be documented in Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs).\
\'95 Evaluation: New digital systems and storage acquisitions must be evaluated against the requirements of this policy and the OAIS functional entities.\
\'95 Review: This policy and the associated technical controls shall be reviewed [Annually] to ensure they remain effective against emerging technological threats.\
\
7. COMPLIANCE AND AUDITING\
\'95 Auditability: The organization shall implement logging and monitoring to provide evidence of compliance with this policy, supporting the principles of ISO 16363.\
\'95 Non-Compliance: Any failure to adhere to preservation protocols that risks the loss of institutional integrity or legal evidence will be addressed via [Organization's Governance/Disciplinary Process].\
\
8. PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT AND METRICS\
To ensure the effectiveness of the digital preservation strategy, the following Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) shall be monitored and reported to the Digital Preservation Steering Committee:\
\
8.1. Data Integrity & Health Metrics\
\'95 Fixity Failure Rate: The percentage of files that failed their most recent checksum verification (Target: < 0.01%).\
\'95 Integrity Check Coverage: The percentage of the total digital archive that has successfully undergone a fixity check within the last [X] months.\
\
8.2. Accessibility & Usability Metrics\
\'95 Format Obsolescence Ratio: The percentage of the archive residing in "at-risk" or proprietary formats vs. sustainable/open standards.\
\'95 Metadata Completeness Score: The percentage of digital objects possessing all mandatory PREMIS metadata fields.\
\
8.3. Operational Efficiency Metrics\
\'95 Detection Lag Time: The duration between a corruption event occurring and its detection by the monitoring system.\
\'95 Automation Percentage: The ratio of automated preservation tasks (e.g., automated fixity) to manual interventions.\
\
8.4. Risk & Compliance Metrics\
\'95 Audit Non-Conformity Count: The number of findings or "fails" identified during internal or external audits.\
\'95 Policy Coverage: The percentage of the organization\'92s total digital estate currently protected under this policy framework.}